  "prompt": "How many lokas (like heaven, hell, earth etc.) are there according to Hindu mythology?",
  "response": "In Hindu mythology, the cosmos is often described as being divided into various \"lokas\" or realms. Traditionally, there are 14 main lokas, which can be categorized into three groups: the higher lokas (heavens), the middle loka (earth), and the lower lokas (hells).\n\n1. **Higher Lokas (Swarga Lokas)**:\n   - Satyaloka (Brahmaloka): The abode of Brahma, the creator.\n   - Tapoloka: The realm of sages and ascetics who perform intense penance.\n   - Janaloka: The realm of the enlightened beings.\n   - Maharloka: The realm of exalted beings who have attained high spiritual achievements.\n   - Svarloka (Swarga): The heavenly realms, often associated with the pleasure and happiness experienced after good karma.\n   - Bhurloka: The earthly realm where humans reside.\n\n2. **Middle Loka**:\n   - Earth (Bhuloka): The physical world where humans live and experience life.\n\n3. **Lower Lokas (Patala Lokas)**:\n   - Atalaloka: The first of the lower realms, inhabited by various beings.\n   - Vitalaloka: A realm associated with various supernatural beings.\n   - Sutalaloka: The abode of powerful beings.\n   - Talataloka: Another subterranean realm.\n   - Mahatala: A realm below the earth.\n   - Rasatala: A realm associated with demons and darker beings.\n   - Patala: The deepest realm, often described as hell.\n\nThese realms are not solely places of reward or punishment but also reflect the various states of existence and consciousness in accordance with karma and spiritual advancement. Different texts may have variations in their descriptions of these lokas, but the overarching concept remains consistent throughout Hindu cosmology.",
